title: For Sale:  RE: guy whining about missing out on the Black Friday sale 1911
postcontent:
Buying a firearm and then advertising it and selling it on Armslist is not illegal. Maybe you should look at page 165 of ATF Federal Firearms Regulations Reference Guide, 2005, (most recent) for discussion of Straw Purchaser.  If one doesn't have a buyer lined up they cannot be buying for another individual, so they are then the true and actual buyer and are making a truthful statement on 4473.

Also, an individual that turns a little profit from standing in line for hours is not engaged in the business of dealing firearms, nor making a livelihood from such, which is illegal without a FFL01.

At least that's the way I read it.

Next year get out of bed and go buy yourself something.

title: For Sale:  New-In-Box VEPR 12GA Shotgun Welded-Folder stock Import-Banned
postcontent:
New-In-Box VEPR 12 gauge shotgun  welded-folder stock. Import-banned.

I am in Northwest Houston / Spring, and I will not travel far to show this. You can travel from wherever you want  in the state, but PLEASE figure out in ADVANCE where Spring, TX is, and decide if that is an acceptable distance to you BEFORE asking for a time and place to meet with me.

I will consider selling to a genuine, eligible adult. You must be able to legally own a firearm, show state photo ID, and fill out bill of sale. I will ask for a photo or scan of TDL before meeting up with you. I will meet in a public place where security cameras are present, and where law enforcement is not far.

 This is not a gunsmith-special or a wall-hanger; it is a new-in-box, never-fired (unless factory-tested), recently-imported (recent year) recognized item. You can read all you want online, and window-shop at some local stores if you really want to look it over, handle, drool, dream, and think about it. I don't want to devote half-hours here and there to people who just want to see one.

If you seem funny or shady, I will simply give up on the possible deal. Individual-to-individual sales in Texas can only be to the eventual, intended, legal owner. If you are trying to buy one of these for a non-eligible friend, or as a gift for a family member, you will have to go elsewhere. Please understand I am just trying to carry out a decent, legitimate, legal deal.

If you are seriously interested and legally eligible to buy, I am a decent person to work with.

Many love the semi-auto shotgun idea, but found the modest-price Saigas to be too much trouble to get working well; those are noted to not be reliable, and to have difficulty with lighter loads. Once the VEPRS were imported, this solved everyone's problems. The VEPR is overall a nicer, more well-constructed firearm.

Reviews say it reliably shoots out of the box, including lighter loads.

I got one of these that was imported before the ban kicked in. Now, they are nowhere. If you find them being sold retail, they are expensive, since they are so rare and no one knows when the ban might be lifted, and how long it might take for any new shipment to reach our shores.

The folding stock is welded in place in order to keep this in the legal "sporting" category, rather than the "semi-auto assault" category. Most reputable sources say that if you replace six parts on these VEPRs with USA-made parts, you will have ten or fewer imported parts, and so you can go ahead and cut the weld in order to have a folding stock.

This possibility is there, but it is up to you and the law. THANKS!
